    time: "7 min",
    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Before any button or light, cinematography is a way of thinking. The camera and the lighting aren't there to record what happened — they're there to <em>tell</em> the audience how to feel about it. Get that idea first, and every technical skill in this course has a purpose to serve.`,
    seoTitle: "Cinematography Fundamentals: What Camera & Light Do for Story | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Cinematography basics for filmmakers — what the camera and lighting actually do for a story, and the mindset that turns a recorded scene into a told one. Chapter 1 of Camera & Lighting Fundamentals.",
    body: `<p>New filmmakers tend to treat the camera as a fancy recording device: point it at the scene, get it in focus, press record. But there's a reason two people can shoot the same actors in the same room and one clip looks flat and amateur while the other looks like cinema. The difference isn't the price of the camera — it's that the second person made a hundred small <em>choices</em> about where to put the lens, how close to be, and how to light the moment, and every one of those choices was in service of the story. Cinematography is the craft of those choices. This chapter is about the mindset behind them, before we get into the tools that execute them.</p>

<h2>Camera and light are storytelling, not recording</h2>

<p>Here's the reframe that changes everything: <strong>every visual choice tells the audience how to feel.</strong> A tight close-up creates intimacy or tension; a wide shot makes a character small and alone. Hard, shadowy light feels dangerous; soft, even light feels safe. A low angle makes someone powerful; a high angle makes them vulnerable. None of this is decoration — it's a second script, written in images, running underneath the dialogue. The audience never consciously notices it, but they feel all of it. Your job as the person behind the camera is to make those choices <em>deliberately</em>, so the picture is saying the same thing as the story. The flat, amateur look almost always comes from making no choice at all — camera at eye level, flat light, whatever framing was easiest — so the images say nothing.</p>

<h2>The two levers: the camera and the light</h2>

<p>Everything in this course comes down to two families of tools, and it helps to hold the whole map in your head from the start:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The camera — how you see.</b> Exposure, shot size, angle, movement, and lens choice determine what's in frame, how it's composed, and how it feels. That's the next few chapters.</li>
  <li><b>The light — what you see.</b> Quality, direction, intensity, and color shape the mood and depth of everything the camera captures. No light, no image; bad light, bad image. That's the heart of this course.</li>
  <li><b>They work together.</b> A great shot is camera and light making the same point. Lighting reveals the shape the lens is framing; the frame gives the light something to fall on.</li>
  <li><b>Intention beats gear.</b> A cheap camera used thoughtfully beats an expensive one used carelessly. The choices are free; the equipment is just how you carry them out.</li>
  <li><b>Serve the story, always.</b> The test for any camera or lighting decision is one question: does this help the audience feel what this moment should make them feel?</li>
</ul>

<div class="pullquote">The difference between footage that looks amateur and footage that looks like cinema usually isn't the camera. It's whether someone made deliberate choices — and every choice was in service of the story.</div>

<p>Keep that story-first question in your pocket as we go. The upcoming chapters will hand you real technical control — exposure, framing, three-point lighting, lenses, color — and it's easy to get lost in the mechanics and forget what they're for. They're for this: turning a recorded event into a told story. Learn the tools, but never let them become the point. The point is always what the audience feels.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>When I'm setting up any shot, I ask one question before I touch the camera: "What is this moment about, and how should it feel?" Tense? Lonely? Warm? Then I choose the frame and the light to say that. It sounds obvious, but most weak footage comes from skipping this — the operator just films the action from wherever they're standing in flat room light. Ten seconds of "what should this feel like?" is the cheapest upgrade to your images you'll ever make, and it costs nothing but the habit.</p>
</div>`,
