    desc: "ISO, aperture, and shutter — the exposure triangle and how to control your image",
    time: "9 min",
    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Exposure is simply how bright or dark your image is — and it's controlled by three settings that trade off against each other: ISO, aperture, and shutter speed. Once you understand how the "exposure triangle" balances, you stop fighting your camera and start commanding it.`,
    seoTitle: "The Exposure Triangle: ISO, Aperture & Shutter for Film | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Camera exposure basics for filmmakers — how ISO, aperture, and shutter speed work together as the exposure triangle, and the 180-degree shutter rule for cinematic motion. Chapter 2 of Camera & Lighting Fundamentals.",
    body: `<p>Auto mode is where images go to look amateur. The camera's automatic exposure guesses at an "average" brightness, which flattens your careful lighting and shifts unpredictably mid-shot. Taking manual control of exposure is the first real step from pointing a camera to operating one — and it's genuinely not hard once the three controls click into place. Think of exposure as a bucket you're filling with light: too little and the image is dark and muddy (underexposed), too much and it's blown out and detail-less (overexposed). Three taps control the flow, and each one costs you something elsewhere. That trade-off is the whole game.</p>

<h2>The three controls — and what each costs</h2>

<p>ISO, aperture, and shutter each change brightness, but each also has a <em>side effect</em> on the look of the image. Understanding the side effect is what lets you choose the right one to adjust:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Aperture (f-stop) — the pupil.</b> How wide the lens opens. A wide aperture (low f-number, e.g. f/2) lets in lots of light <em>and</em> gives a shallow, blurry-background look; a narrow aperture (f/11) is darker but keeps more in focus. Its side effect is depth of field (Chapter 9).</li>
  <li><b>Shutter speed — the blinds.</b> How long each frame is exposed. Slower lets in more light but adds motion blur; faster is darker and crisper, even strobey. For film, this one is mostly locked — see below.</li>
  <li><b>ISO — the amplifier.</b> How much the sensor boosts the signal. Higher ISO brightens a dark image but adds grain/noise; lower ISO is cleanest. Keep it as low as your light allows.</li>
  <li><b>They balance.</b> Open the aperture and you can lower the ISO; you're always trading one for another to hit correct brightness with the look you want.</li>
  <li><b>Read the image, not just the meter.</b> Use tools like the histogram and zebras to judge exposure precisely rather than trusting the camera's auto guess.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The shutter rule that makes motion look like film</h2>

<p>Here's the one specific rule worth memorizing, because it separates footage that looks "video-ish" from footage that looks cinematic: the <strong>180-degree shutter rule.</strong> Set your shutter speed to roughly double your frame rate. Shooting at 24 frames per second? Set shutter to 1/48 (or the nearest option, 1/50). At 30fps, use 1/60. This produces the natural amount of motion blur our eyes associate with cinema. Too fast a shutter makes movement look unnaturally sharp and juddery (the "Saving Private Ryan" battle look — great as a deliberate choice, jarring by accident); too slow makes it smeary. Because you're keeping shutter locked to your frame rate for that cinematic motion, in practice you usually leave shutter alone and balance exposure with <strong>aperture, ISO, and the amount of light you add</strong> — which is exactly why lighting (the rest of this course) and exposure are two halves of one skill. And when there's too much light for a wide aperture at your locked shutter and low ISO — bright daylight, say — the professional tool is an <strong>ND filter</strong>, essentially sunglasses for your lens, which cuts light without touching any of the three settings. Master this balance and you'll always get a clean, correctly exposed, cinematic image, on any camera.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Exposure is a bucket you fill with light, and every control that fills it faster costs you something — background blur, motion feel, or grain. Knowing the cost is what turns three settings into deliberate choices.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My working order on set is: lock shutter to my frame rate (1/48 at 24fps) and forget it; set ISO to the camera's cleanest native value; then set exposure with aperture and, most of all, with <em>light</em> — adding or cutting it until the image looks right at the aperture I want for the shot. If it's too bright outside for that, I reach for an ND filter, not a faster shutter. Getting exposure from light rather than from cranking settings is the habit that keeps footage clean and cinematic instead of grainy or strobey.</p>
</div>`,
