    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Shot sizes are the vocabulary of film. Wide, medium, close-up — each is a different word, and choosing the right one is how you control what the audience looks at and how they feel about it. Learn the shots and the framing principles, and you can compose a picture that speaks.`,
    seoTitle: "Camera Shots in Filmmaking: Shot Sizes & Framing | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Camera shots in filmmaking — the shot sizes from wide to extreme close-up, what each one says, and the framing principles that make a composition work. Chapter 3 of Camera & Lighting Fundamentals.",
    body: `<p>Every shot you frame answers a question for the audience: <em>where do I look, and how close am I to this?</em> The shot size — how much of the subject fills the frame — is the main way you answer it, and each size carries its own feeling. A wide shot puts a character in context, small against their world; a close-up presses us right up against their face, where every flicker of feeling reads. Choosing shots isn't a mechanical checklist. It's deciding, moment to moment, how intimate the audience should be with what's happening. This chapter gives you the vocabulary and the framing rules to make those decisions on purpose.</p>

<h2>The shot sizes and what they say</h2>

<p>Learn these as a ladder from far to near — and, more importantly, learn what each one <em>does</em> emotionally:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Wide / establishing shot.</b> Shows the whole location and where people are in it. Sets context and geography; makes characters feel small, isolated, or part of something bigger.</li>
  <li><b>Full shot.</b> The whole body, head to toe. Good for physical action and body language, keeping us at an observational distance.</li>
  <li><b>Medium shot.</b> Roughly waist up — the everyday "conversation" shot. Neutral and natural, close enough to read expression, wide enough for gesture.</li>
  <li><b>Close-up.</b> The face fills the frame. Maximum intimacy and emotion; this is where performance lands hardest. Spend them where the feeling matters most.</li>
  <li><b>Extreme close-up &amp; wide (extreme long) shot.</b> The extremes — a single eye or a detail for intensity; a tiny figure in a vast landscape for scale and loneliness. Powerful used sparingly.</li>
</ul>

<p>The craft is in the <em>sequence</em> of these. Cutting from a wide to a close-up pulls the audience in; the wider you've been, the more a sudden close-up hits. Coverage — shooting a scene in several sizes so you can cut between them — is a whole discipline (see the Shot List course), but it starts with knowing what each size means so you choose them for story, not habit.</p>

<h2>Framing: composing inside the rectangle</h2>

<p>Once you've chosen a size, framing is how you arrange things within the frame, and a few reliable principles lift a composition from snapshot to cinematic:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Rule of thirds.</b> Place your subject and key lines a third of the way in, not dead centre. Put eyes on the upper third-line. It's the default that just looks right — and worth breaking deliberately, not by accident.</li>
  <li><b>Headroom and looking room.</b> Leave a little space above the head (not too much), and more space in the direction a person looks or moves, so the frame doesn't feel cramped or off-balance.</li>
  <li><b>Lead the eye.</b> Use lines, light, and focus to steer the viewer to what matters. The brightest, sharpest, most contrasting thing wins the eye — so make sure it's the right thing.</li>
  <li><b>Foreground, mid, background.</b> Layer depth into the frame. Something in the foreground and a deep background turn a flat image into a three-dimensional world.</li>
  <li><b>Keep it clean.</b> Watch the edges and background — a pole "growing" out of a head, clutter behind the actor. A tidy frame reads as intentional; a messy one reads as amateur.</li>
</ul>

<div class="pullquote">Every shot answers one question for the audience — where do I look, and how close am I to this? Shot size is how you answer it, and each size is a different feeling.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Before I lock any frame, I run my eyes around the <em>edges</em> and the background, not just the subject — that's where amateur shots are made or saved. Is a lamp sprouting from her head? Is there a bright distracting window stealing the eye? Is the background just cluttered noise? Ninety percent of "why does my footage look amateur?" is uncomposed backgrounds and dead-centre framing. Fix the edges, put the subject on a third, add a little depth, and the same camera suddenly looks like you knew what you were doing — because now you did.</p>
</div>`,
