    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Where you put the camera in height, and whether you move it, are two more storytelling controls hiding in plain sight. The angle changes the power in a shot; movement changes its energy. Used with intent they're powerful — used at random they quietly undermine the scene.`,
    seoTitle: "Camera Angles & Movement in Filmmaking | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Camera angles and movement in filmmaking — high, low, and eye-level angles and what they mean, plus pans, tilts, dollies, and handheld, and when motion earns its place. Chapter 4 of Camera & Lighting Fundamentals.",
    body: `<p>Two shots can be the same size and yet feel completely different depending on the angle and whether the camera moves. Angle and movement are the finishing controls of framing — subtle, powerful, and easy to get wrong. The overarching rule, which applies to both, is the one from Chapter 1 turned into a discipline: <em>do it for a reason.</em> A dramatic low angle or a sweeping move is thrilling when it means something and cheesy when it doesn't. Let's take angle and movement in turn.</p>

<h2>Angle: height changes power</h2>

<p>The vertical position of the camera relative to your subject is a direct dial on how powerful or vulnerable they feel:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Eye level.</b> The neutral default — we meet the character as an equal. Most shots live here, and that's correct; it's honest and unobtrusive.</li>
  <li><b>Low angle (looking up).</b> Makes the subject loom large — powerful, dominant, heroic, or threatening. The hero shot, the villain's entrance.</li>
  <li><b>High angle (looking down).</b> Makes the subject smaller and weaker — vulnerable, trapped, diminished. We literally look down on them.</li>
  <li><b>Dutch tilt (canted).</b> Tilting the horizon off-level creates unease, disorientation, or wrongness. A strong spice — a little goes a long way.</li>
  <li><b>Point of view &amp; over-the-shoulder.</b> POV puts us in a character's eyes; OTS frames one person past another's shoulder, tying two people together in a conversation.</li>
</ul>

<p>Because eye level is neutral, the moment you leave it you're making a statement — so make sure the statement is true. Shooting a powerful character from a high angle undercuts them; shooting a victim from below confuses the audience. Match the angle to the power dynamic you want.</p>

<h2>Movement: motion changes energy</h2>

<p>A moving camera adds energy, reveals information, and follows action — but every move should be motivated. The main tools, roughly from simplest to most involved:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Pan &amp; tilt.</b> Pivoting the camera horizontally (pan) or vertically (tilt) on a fixed point — to follow a subject or reveal something. Cheap and effective.</li>
  <li><b>Dolly / tracking.</b> Physically moving the whole camera — in, out, or alongside. A slow push-in builds intensity; a track keeps pace with a walking character. The classic "cinematic" move.</li>
  <li><b>Handheld.</b> Camera on the shoulder — immediate, raw, energetic, documentary. Great for tension and realism; nauseating when overused or just shaky.</li>
  <li><b>Gimbal / Steadicam.</b> Stabilized floating movement — smooth glides through space. Modern and accessible with cheap gimbals, but easy to overuse into pointless drifting.</li>
  <li><b>The default: lock it off.</b> A still, well-composed static shot is often the strongest choice. Movement should earn its place, not fill silence.</li>
</ul>

<div class="pullquote">Leave eye level and you're making a statement about power; move the camera and you're adding energy. Both are powerful when they mean something — and cheesy the moment they don't.</div>

<p>The trap on low-budget films, now that a $100 gimbal makes smooth movement easy, is <em>constant</em> motion — every shot drifting for no reason, which reads as restless amateur "coverage" rather than intention. Discipline is the mark of the pro: move the camera when the story wants energy or a reveal, and let it be still the rest of the time so that when you <em>do</em> move, it lands. Angle and movement are seasoning. A meal that's all seasoning is inedible.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My rule with a gimbal is that I have to be able to finish the sentence "the camera moves here because…" If the honest answer is "because I have a gimbal and moving looks cool," I lock it off instead. The most confident-looking indie films use mostly static, well-composed shots and save movement for a handful of motivated moments — a push-in as a realization lands, a track as someone flees. The nervous-looking ones drift constantly. Stillness is not the absence of technique; it's often the most advanced choice on the day.</p>
</div>`,
