    dek: `Lighting looks like a dark art until you realize it's just four controls: quality, direction, intensity, and color. Every lighting setup you'll ever build — from a single lamp to a full rig — is a combination of those four. Understand them and you can light anything, with anything.`,
    seoTitle: "How Light Works: Film Lighting Basics | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Film lighting basics — the four properties of light every filmmaker controls: quality (hard vs soft), direction, intensity, and color. The foundation of lighting a scene. Chapter 5 of Camera & Lighting Fundamentals.",
    body: `
<p>Lighting is the part of cinematography that most intimidates beginners and most separates amateur footage from professional. But it isn't mysterious. Light has exactly four properties you can control, and cinematographers spend their careers just combining these four in different ways. Once you can name what a light is doing — is it hard or soft? where's it coming from? how bright? what color? — you can look at any image you admire, reverse-engineer it, and recreate it. This chapter gives you that language, before we assemble it into setups in the next chapters.</p>

<h2>The four properties of light</h2>

<p>Learn to see these consciously and you'll never look at a lit image the same way again:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Quality — hard vs. soft.</b> The single most important property. <em>Hard</em> light (a bare bulb, direct sun) casts sharp, dark-edged shadows — dramatic, harsh, high-contrast. <em>Soft</em> light (an overcast sky, a big diffused source) wraps gently with soft-edged shadows — flattering, natural, gentle. The rule: the <em>bigger the source relative to the subject</em>, the softer the light.</li>
  <li><b>Direction — where it comes from.</b> Front light flattens; side light reveals texture and shape (the workhorse of dramatic lighting); back light separates the subject from the background; top and bottom light feel unnatural or spooky. Direction sculpts the face.</li>
  <li><b>Intensity — how bright.</b> How much light, and crucially the <em>ratio</em> between your bright and dark areas (contrast). A big difference between light and shadow feels dramatic and moody; a small difference feels flat and even.</li>
  <li><b>Color — the temperature and tint.</b> Light has color, from warm orange to cool blue (covered fully in Chapter 10). Color sets mood — warm feels cozy or nostalgic, cool feels cold or clinical.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The most important idea: soft vs. hard, and size</h2>

<p>If you take one thing from this chapter, take the relationship between <strong>source size and softness</strong>, because it's the lever you'll pull most and it's free. A small, bare light source is hard — think of the sharp, unflattering shadow a phone flashlight throws under someone's nose. Make that same light bigger and softer — bounce it off a wall, shoot it through a bedsheet or a diffusion panel, or move it closer so it's relatively larger — and the shadows melt into something gentle and beautiful. This is why professionals are forever <em>softening and shaping</em> light rather than just adding more of it. A single cheap lamp bounced off a white ceiling can look gorgeous; the same lamp pointed straight at a face looks like an interrogation. You don't need expensive fixtures to get great light — you need to understand quality and direction and shape whatever light you have. That principle is what makes the budget lighting in Chapter 8 possible, and it's the foundation of the three-point setup we build next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Light has just four controls — quality, direction, intensity, and color. Every setup ever made is a combination of those four, which means once you can name what a light is doing, you can recreate any look you admire.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Train your eye off the set: start noticing light in real life. Watch how soft window light on an overcast day flatters a face, how hard noon sun carves ugly shadows under the eyes, how a warm lamp feels different from cool daylight. Every gorgeous image you see in a film or a photo, ask "hard or soft? from where? what color?" Reverse-engineering light you admire is the fastest way to learn to make it — and it costs nothing but attention. Cinematographers are just people who never stopped watching how light behaves.</p>
</div>
`,
