    kicker: "Putting It to Work",
    dek: `The lens is the eye of the camera, and swapping it changes the feel of a shot as much as moving the camera does. Two ideas do most of the work: focal length — how wide or tight the lens sees — and depth of field, the blurry-background look everyone wants. Here's how to wield both.`,
    seoTitle: "Camera Lenses & Depth of Field for Filmmakers | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Camera lenses and depth of field explained — focal length (wide vs telephoto), how lens choice changes the feel of a shot, and how to control shallow depth of field. Chapter 9 of Camera & Lighting Fundamentals.",
    body: `
<p>People obsess over cameras, but experienced shooters know the <em>lens</em> shapes the image more than the camera body does. A lens has two properties you control for creative effect: its <strong>focal length</strong> (measured in millimeters — how wide or narrow its view is) and its <strong>aperture</strong> (which we met in Chapter 2 as an exposure control, but which also governs depth of field). Understanding what each does lets you pick the right glass for the feeling you want, instead of just shooting on whatever's attached.</p>

<h2>Focal length: wide vs. telephoto</h2>

<p>Focal length changes not just how much fits in frame, but how space itself <em>feels</em>:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Wide lenses (e.g. 16–35mm).</b> See a broad view, exaggerate depth and distance, and make spaces feel large. Great for establishing shots and immersive movement. Up close they distort — noses and foreground loom — which can feel dynamic or grotesque.</li>
  <li><b>Normal lenses (around 35–50mm).</b> Roughly match how the human eye sees — natural, undramatic perspective. A safe, honest default for much of a film.</li>
  <li><b>Telephoto lenses (85mm+).</b> See a narrow slice, compress distance (backgrounds feel closer and bigger), and flatter faces. Classic for close-ups and portraits; they isolate the subject and pull the world in behind them.</li>
  <li><b>Perspective is about distance, not just the lens.</b> A wide lens makes you move <em>in</em> close (distorting), a long lens makes you stand <em>back</em> (flattening). That change in your physical distance is what really warps or flatters a face.</li>
  <li><b>Prime vs. zoom.</b> Primes (fixed focal length) are usually sharper, wider-aperture, and cheaper for the quality; zooms are convenient. Many indie shooters build a look on a few good primes.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Depth of field: the blurry-background look, controlled</h2>

<p>Depth of field is how much of the image is in sharp focus, from near to far — and the shallow, creamy-background look (the background melting to blur behind a sharp subject) is what most people mean by "cinematic." It's not magic or expensive; it's controlled by three things you now understand. <strong>A wider aperture</strong> (low f-number like f/2) gives shallower focus — this is the main dial. <strong>A longer focal length</strong> (telephoto) gives shallower focus. And <strong>getting closer to your subject</strong>, with more distance behind them to the background, gives shallower focus. Stack those — a longish lens, wide open, close to your subject, with the background far away — and you get that dreamy separation. Reverse them for deep focus where everything's sharp (a wide lens at f/8 keeps the whole scene crisp, useful for landscapes or ensemble staging). But two cautions worth their own line: shallow focus is a <em>tool, not a goal</em> — beginners blur everything and end up with soft, hard-to-follow footage where you can't even tell what's happening; use it to guide the eye, not to show off. And shallow focus is <em>unforgiving</em> — the thinner your focus, the easier it is to miss it entirely, so on a run-and-gun day a slightly deeper stop that keeps your actor reliably sharp beats a gorgeous blur that's soft on the eyes. Serve the story, as always: blur the background when isolating the subject helps the moment, and keep depth when the geography matters.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The "cinematic" blurry background isn't magic or money — it's a longer lens, a wider aperture, and getting close with the background far away. But shallow focus is a tool to guide the eye, not a goal to chase.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>New shooters fall in love with shallow focus and shoot everything wide open at f/1.4 — then half the footage is soft because the focus missed by an inch, and the audience can't tell where to look. I pull back from that on real shoots: I'll shoot a bit stopped down (say f/2.8–f/4) so my actor stays reliably sharp, and reserve the ultra-shallow look for a specific isolating close-up where it earns its place. A slightly deeper image that's <em>in focus</em> always beats a dreamy one that isn't. Focus is a story tool; missing it is just a mistake.</p>
</div>
`,
